SUBJECT:  INSTALLATION OF DUAL PRINTER INTERFACE IN 7/32 AND ENGINE.


               DUE TO BACKPLANE DIFFERENCES BETWEEN THE INTERDATA 7/32
               AND THE TYMNET ENGINE, IT IS NECESSARY TO CHANGE THE
               INSTALLATION PROCEDURES FOR THE DUAL PRINTER INTERFACE.

               THE UPDATED PROCEDURE, AVAILABLE BY PRINTING
               (CES:8)@PTRREV1, REPLACES THE SHEET TITLED
               "SECTION II  INSTALLATION" OF THE "I-7/32 DUAL
               PRINTER INTERFACE, TECHNICAL REFERRENCE MANUAL".



ACTION:        PRINT THIS REVISED PROCEDURE AND UPDATE YOUR COPY
               OF THE TECHNICAL REFERRENCE MANUAL.

         NOTE: IF YOU DO NOT HAVE THE TECHNICAL REFERRENCE MANUAL,
               PLEASE SUBMIT AN ORDER FOR COPIES SUFFICIENT FOR YOUR
               REGION TO CESMAIL:8. ANY COPIES  ORDERED FROM CES WILL
               HAVE THIS UPDATE INCORPORATED.


CFB NO.:    3                                        DATE:  AUGUST 16, 1979   

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  SOFTWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  CREATING .NIB FILES UNDER NAD FOR DOWNSTREAM LOADING


               THE NODE ASSEMBLER DEBUGGER (NAD) WILL READ AND WRITE
               IMAGE BINARY FILES WHICH CONTAIN INFORMATION
               NECESSARY TO LOAD AND DUMP MEMORY IMAGES FOR TYMNET
               ENGINES AND INTERDATA 7/32'S.

               A NIB FILE IS REQUIRED IN ORDER TO USE LOADII TO
               DOWNSTREAM LOAD TYMNET ENGINES OR INTERDATA 7/32'S
               WITH EITHER REMOTE CODE OR ISIS KERNEL (SLOT 0) CODE.
               THE FOLLOWING PROCEDURES INDICATE HOW TO CREATE A NIB
               FILE FOR BOTH APPLICATIONS:

METHOD 1       TO CREATE A NIB FILE OF REMOTE CODE FOR NODE ABC.
               ************************************************

-R NAD
XXYYZZ         :NAD RESPONDS WITH DATE OF CURRENT VERSION

;@   (TYMNET)NODENAME.TYM   :ASSEMBLE TYM FILE FOR NODE ABC
END OF ASSEMBLY

;@   (TYMNET)I417.NAD       :ASSEMBLE CODE
END OF ASSEMBLY

;F   NODENAME.NIB           :COMMAND TO NAD TO NAME NIB FILE
0,DEND;P       :(NO C/R) GIVE NAD BEGINNING ADDRESS AND BYTE COUNT TO LOAD
4F4;T          :(NO C/R) PROVIDE START ADDRESS OF CODE
%Q             :TO EXIT FROM NAD

               THE NIB FILE "NODENAME.NIB" WILL NOW BE IN YOUR DIRECTORY
               AND MAY BE USED IN CONJUNCTION WITH LOADII TO LOAD NODE ABC.

 METHOD 2      TO CREATE A NIB FILE OF ISIS CODE FOR NODE ABC.
               **********************************************

-R NAD
XXYYZZ         :NAD RESPONDS WITH DATE OF CURRENT VERSION

;X   (TYMISIS)NODABC.CMD    :ASSEMBLE ISIS CODE USING CMD FILE

               :AFTER THE CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS AND VARIOUS ASSEMBLIES
               :ARE COMPLETED NAD WILL EVENTUALLY RESPOND WITH -

END OF ASSEMBLY

;F   NODABC.NIB             :COMMAND TO NAD TO NAME THE NIB FILE
0,IEND;P       :(NO C/R) GIVE NAD BEGINNING ADDRESS AND BYTE COUNT TO LOAD
70;T           :(NO C/R) PROVIDE START ADDRESS OF CODE
%Q             :TO EXIT FROM NAD

               THE NIB FILE "NODABC.NIB" WILL NOW BE IN YOUR DIRECTORY
               AND MAY BE USED IN CONJUNCTION WITH LOADII TO LOAD ISIS
               KERNEL (SLOT 0) CODE INTO NODE ABC.

               FOR MORE INFORMATION ON NAD IMAGE BINARY CONSULT
               (ISISDOC:33)NIB.DOC


CFB NO.:    4                                        DATE:  AUGUST 20, 1979   

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  VADIC 202T
SUBJECT:  CABLE PROBLEM WITH ASC140-18JP USED WITH VADIC 202T


                               CONNECTIONS.


PROBLEM:       SOME ASC140-18 CABLES WERE MANUFACTURED WITH THE MALE
               AND FEMALE CONNECTORS MOUNTED ON THE WRONG ENDS. THESE
               FAULTY CABLES ARE RECOGNISABLE BY HAVING THE CABLE TYPE
               PRINTED ON A WHITE PLASTIC SLEEVE. THE BAD CABLE IS
               ALSO RECOGNISABLE BY THE FOLLOWING PINS ON THE MALE
               CONNECTOR:
                               PINS 2,3,6,7,8,&20.

               THE CORRECT CABLES HAVE THE TYPE STAMPED DIRECTLY ON THE
               CABLE AND HAS THE FOLLOWING PINS ON THE MALE CONNECTOR:

                               PINS 2,3,4,7,8,&20.


ACTION:        IF YOU HAVE ANY OF THESE FAULTY CABLES IN YOUR REGION,
               TAG THEM AS DEFECTIVE AND RETURN TO MANUFACTURING FOR
               REWORK.


CFB NO.:    5                                        DATE:  AUGUST 22, 1979   

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  ENGINE MICROCODE DIAGNOSTIC DISPLAYING "1E9 DEAD"



               THERE APPEARS TO BE RECURRING INCIDENTS IN THE FIELD OF
               CRASHES ON ENGINES RESULTING IN A CONSOLE DISPLAY OF
               '1E9 DEAD'.
               WHAT EXACTLY DOES THIS MEAN? -
               THE CPU HAS SEEN (VIA THE ATN0 LINE GOING ACTIVE) THAT
               A DEVICE ON THE I/O BUS WANTS TO INTERRUPT. AS THERE
               MAY BE MULTIPLE DEVICES ON THE I/O BUS ALL INTERRUPTING
               THE CPU, THE CPU SENDS OUT TACK0/RACK0 TO LATCH UP THE
               HIGHEST PRIORITY INTERRUPT.
               RACK0 IS TRAPPED BY THE DEVICE AND IT WILL THEN PUT ITS
               ADDRESS ON THE I/O BUS. WHEN THE ADDRESS IS STABLE THE
               DEVICE SENDS SYN0 BACK TO THE CPU AND THE CPU THEN
               TAKES THE ADDRESS OFF THE BUS AND UTILISES IT TO ENTER
               THE APPROPRIATE INTERRUPT ROUTINE.

               A CRASH OF '1E9 DEAD' MEANS THAT THE CPU TIMED OUT
               AWAITING THE SYN0 REPONSE AFTER SENDING RACK0.

               THIS CAN BE DUE TO A NUMBER OF PROBLEMS:

          (1)  THE RACK0/TACK0 CHAIN IS BROKEN ABOVE THE SLOT
               CONTAINING THE INTERRUPTING DEVICE. I.E. THE DEVICE
               WILL NEVER RECEIVE RACK0, AND HENCE WILL NEVER
               RESPOND WITH SYN0.

          (2)  NOISE ON RACK0 LINE CAUSES THE DEVICE TO THINK THE
               CPU HAS ALREADY SEEN SYN0 AND HAS TAKEN THE ADDRESS
               OFF THE BUS. THE DEVICE CLEARS ITS INTERRUPT AND DROPS
               SYN0 BEFORE THE CPU HAS ACTUALLY LOOKED AT SYN0.


ACTION:        SOLUTION TO PROBLEM (1) IS OBVIOUSLY TO ENSURE THE
               RACK0/TACK0 CHAIN IS CORRECT ON THE BACKPLANE.

               SOLUTION TO PROBLEM (2) IS DEPENDENT ON THE NOISE
               SOURCE FOR THE RACK0/TACK0 CHAIN.

           (A) POSSIBLE CAUSE IS IC AT LOCATION "C8" ON MULTIFUNCTION
               BOARD (ASB 252-1). IF THIS CHIP IS A 74LS244, CHANGE TO
               A 74S244. (REFER TO ECO 79-45).

           (B) ANOTHER SOURCE OF NOISE CAN BE THE I/O CONTROL SIGNAL
               RECEIVERS ON THE SYNC I/F (ASB 212-1). IC CHIP AT
               LOCATION D2 IS A 74LS04. IT CAN BE CHANGED TO A 7404
               BUT THIS IS NOT A STANDARD CHANGE AND IS NOT RECOMMENDED
               UNTIL AN ECO IS RELEASED. (AN ECO IS DUE FOR RELEASE FROM
               ENGINEERING. AS SOON AS IT IS, THIS BULLETIN WILL BE
               UPDATED).

         NOTE: CHECK ALSO THE FOLLOWING ECO'S ARE INSTALLED ON THE
               MULTIFUNCTION CARD-
                                       ECO 79-20


CFB NO.:    7                                        DATE:  SEPTEMBER  3, 1979

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  INTERDATA7/32
SUBJECT:  3600 BAUD CLOCK OUTPUT FROM MULTI-FUNCTION CARD (ASB197-3)


PROBLEM:       A SCHEMATIC ERROR EXISTS ON PAGE 2 OF 12 FOR THE WIRE-WRAP
               MULTIFUNCTION CARD (ASB197-3). AT CO-ORDS G3, THE 3600
               OUTPUT OF IC E6 PIN 6 IS SHOWN GOING TO THE BACKPLANE PIN
               125 CONNECTOR 0. ON THE BOARD ITSELF, THE 3600 OUTPUT GOES
               TO THE BACKPLANE PIN 225 CONNECTOR 0. AN ECO IS BEING
               GENERATED TO CORRECT THIS SCHEMATIC ERROR.
               THE 3600 OUTPUT IS USED TO CLOCK THE TRANSMIT DATA LATCHES
               ON THE ASYNCHRONOUS INTERFACE. ON INTERDATA 7/32'S, THIS
               WAS INCORPORATED BY ECO'S 77-4, 77-5, & 77-6.
               ECO 77-4 REVISED THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD (ASB197-2) TO LEVEL
               3 BY PROVIDING THE 3600 OUTPUT.
               ECO 77-5 REVISED THE I/O BACKPLANE TO PROVIDE 3600 OUTPUT
               ON ALL SLOTS WHERE THE ASYNC CARD MAY BE INSTALLED.
               ECO 77-6 REVISED THE ASYNC I/F ITSELF TO INCORPORATE THE
               TRANSMIT DATA LATCHES.
               IT IS IMPORTANT TO ENSURE THAT ECO 77-5 WAS INSTALLED
               CORRECTLY ON INTERDATA 7/32'S TO PICK UP THE 3600 OUTPUT
               FROM PIN 225 AND NOT PIN 125 OF THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD SLOT.

               EVIDENTLY THIS ECO WAS INSTALLED INCORRECTLY IN SOME MACHINES,
               AS PER THE SCHEMATIC ERROR, RESULTING IN NO TRANSMIT DATA, AND
               THUS DEAD PORTS.

        NOTE:  THE NEW MULTIFUNCTION CARD (ASB252-1) ALSO OUTPUTS 3600 ON
               PIN 225 CONNECTOR 0.
               ON THE TYMNET ENGINE, FOR ALL I/O SLOTS:
               PIN 125 IS CONNECTED BY CHAIN DOWN BACKPLANE
               PIN 225 IS CONNECTED BY CHAIN DOWN BACKPLANE
               ALSO, THE ASYNC I/F (ASB211-1) ON BOARD JUMPERS PIN 125 TO
               PIN 225 ON CONNECTOR 0.
               HENCE, THE WIRE-WRAP MULTIFUNCTION CARD (ASB197-3) IN A TYMNET
               ENGINE, DOES NOT EXHIBIT THIS PROBLEM.
               IT WILL ONLY BE EVIDENT ON INTERDATA 7/32'S WHERE THE BACK-
               PLANE REVISION WAS INSTALLED INCORRECTLY BY PICKING OFF THE
               3600 OUTPUT FROM THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD SLOT ON PIN 125
               INSTEAD OF PIN 225 CONNECTOR 0.


CFB NO.:    8                                        DATE:  SEPTEMBER 10, 1979

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  TYMNET ENGINE INSTALLATION


PROBLEM:       POSSIBLE MAJOR DAMAGE MAY BE CAUSED TO ALL PC BOARDS
               CONNECTED TO THE I/O (MUX) BUS BY INCORRECT INSTALLATION
               OF THE I/O TERMINATORS OR MEMORY TERMINATORS.
               THIS CAN RESULT IN + OR - 16.5 VOLTS BEING APPLIED TO
               THE MUX BUS TRANSCEIVERS.

WARNING:       WHEN INSTALLING AN ENGINE, ENSURE THAT THE CBB190 & 191
               I/O TERMINATORS ARE ALIGNED WITH PINS 0 - 41 AND THE
               COMPONENT SIDE IS UPPERMOST.


CFB NO.:    9                                        DATE:  SEPTEMBER 10, 1979

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  VARIAN
SUBJECT:  NEW V72 OPTION BOARD (DM357 REV DF OR ABOVE) SWITCH SETTINGS


ACTION:        A NEW REVISION VARIAN V72 OPTION BOARD HAS REACHED THE
               FIELD. THIS BOARD HAS A GROUP OF DIP SWITCHES AT CO-ORDS
               T9 WHICH ENABLE OR DISABLE A NEW FEATURE WHICH TYMSHARE
               CURRENTLY DOES NOT USE. THESE FOUR SWITCHES SHOULD BE SET
               TO THE "A" (DISABLE) POSITION. THE "B" (ENABLE) POSITION
               SHOULD NOT BE SET, AS THIS WILL CAUSE PARITY ERRORS TO
               BE IGNORED.









