TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  DEFECTIVE BUS TRANSCEIVER CHIPS (2907'S) ON ROM &I/O


PROBLEM:       SOME ROM & I/O BOARDS REACHED THE FIELD WITH DEFECTIVE
               QUAD BUS TRANSCEIVER CHIPS (2907) AT CO-ORDS L1,M1,N1,P1
               R1, AND S1. THE CHIPS CAN BE RECOGNISED BY HAVING A DATE CODE
               STAMP OF 7919. THESE CHIPS ARE USED FOR THE DATA AND CONTROL
               INTERFACE TO THE I/O BUS.

ACTION:        CHECK ALL ROM & I/O BOARDS AT YOUR EARLIEST CONVENIENCE FOR
               THESE DEFECTIVE CHIPS AND ORDER REPLACEMENT CHIPS VIA
               JOHN AVIGDOR, CUPERTINO.


CFB NO.:   11                                        DATE:  OCTOBER  2, 1979  

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  INCORRECT BLOWER FAN FILTER ON TYMNET ENGINE


PROBLEM:       INCORRECT FILTER MATERIAL WAS USED ON THE ENGINE BLOWER FAN
               CAUSING SEVERELY RESTRICTED AIR FLOW THROUGH THE MACHINE
               AND HENCE, POSSIBLE OVERHEATING OF PC BOARDS.

ACTION:        REMOVE GRILL FROM FRONT OF BLOWER ASSEMBLY. REMOVE FOAM
               FILTER MATERIAL FROM GRILL AND HOLD IN FRONT OF BRIGHT LIGHT.
               IF YOU CAN SEE A REASONABLE AMOUNT OF LIGHT THROUGH THE
               FILTER IT IS O.K. AND MAY BE REUSED. IF YOU CAN SEE ALMOST
               NO LIGHT THROUGH FILTER, DISCARD IT AND REPLACE GRILL
               WITHOUT ANY FILTER MATERIAL. (THERE IS A SECONDARY FILTER
               BEHIND THE GRILL WHICH WILL PREVENT EXCESSIVE DIRT OR
               PARTICLES FROM ENTERING THE MACHINE.)

       NOTE:   THE INCORRECT MATERIAL IS A DARK GREY FOAM WHICH CLOSELY
               RESEMBLES "PACKING MATERIAL" AS OPPOSED TO A POROUS FILTER
               MATERIAL.
               ORDER QUANTITIES OF FILTER REPLACEMENT FROM COMMUNICATIONS
               MAINTENANCE SPARE PARTS (JOHN AVIGDOR).


CFB NO.:   12                                        DATE:  OCTOBER  9, 1979  

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  SOFTWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  ENGINE REMOTE CODE ERROR HALTS/DISPLAYS


               THE FOLLOWING BULLETIN DESCRIBES THE ERROR HALTS THAT CAN
               OCCUR DURING ENGINE REMOTE CODE EXECUTION. THE HALT
               INDICATIONS SHOULD ASSIST IN UTILISING THE CODE TO
               DETERMINE MACHINE PROBLEMS.
               THE SOURCE INFORMATION FOR THIS BULLETIN WAS DERIVED FROM
               THE FOLLOWING DOCUMENT: (RFORKISH:33)FE422.DOC

               1. CODE HALTS AT LOCATION "81" OR "82" IMMEDIATELY AFTER
                 RESTART OR HALTS AT LOCATION "810" ANYTIME - MACHINE IS
                 GENERATING AN INTERRUPT ON A DEVICE NOT EXPECTED BY THE
                 REMOTE CODE. THE OFFENDING DEVICE ADDRESS IS IN REGISTER
                 2 OF REGISTER SET 0 (MACHINE IS IN REGISTER SET 0 AFTER
                 INTERRUPT IS TAKEN).

               2. MACHINE DISPLAYS "BAD1" ON LEFT HALF OF CONSOND A
                 VALUE FROM "22" TO "5F" ON RIGHT HALF OF CONSOLE -
                 MACHINE IS GENERATING AN INTERRUPT ON A SYNCHRONOUS LINE
                 WHICH IS NOT VALID FOR THIS CONFIGURATION. THE RIGHT
                 CONSOLE VALUE INDICATES THE OFFENDING ADDRESS: "22" OR "23"
                 FOR SYNC LINE 1, "24" OR "25" FOR SYNC LINE 2, "3E" OR "3F"
                 FOR SYNC LINE 15, "40" OR "41" FOR SYNC LINE 16, "5E" OR
                 "5F" FOR SYNC LINE 31. THIS PROBLEM CAUSES A HALT AT
                 LOCATION "84" IN CODE RELEASES PRIOR TO VERSION 422, WITH
                 THE OFFENDING ADDRESS IN REGISTER 2 OF SET 0.
                 TYPICAL CAUSES OF THIS HALT ARE:-

               (A) A SYNC LINE HAS BEEN CONNECTED FOR WHICH THE CODE HAS
                  NOT BEEN ASSEMBLED. CHECK THE LINES CONNECTED AGAINST
                  THE .TYM FILE FOR THIS CONFIGURATION.
               (B) A HARDWIRED CLOCK SOURCE HAS BEEN JUMPERED ON THE SYNC
                  CARD TO A LINE NOT ASSEMBLED IN THIS CODE.
               (C) NOISE ON THE TRANSMIT AND/OR RECEIVE CLOCK PATH IS
                  CAUSING SPURIOUS INTERRUPTS TO BE GENERATED FOR
                  UNASSIGNED LINES.

               3. CODE HALTS AT LOCATION "2D0" IMMEDIATELY AFTER STARTUP.
                  PROBABLY CAUSED BY .TYM FILE ERROR IN SPECIFYING MORE
                  MEMORY THAN THE MACHINE ACTUALLY CONTAINS, ALTHOUGH
                  COULD BE CAUSED BY MEMORY FAILURE. CHECK "NBRK" PARAMETER
                  IN .TYM FILE.

               4. CODE HALTS AT LOCATION "238" IMMEDIATELY AFTER STARTUP.
                  REMOTE PURPOSELY MADE AN ILLEGAL MEMORY REFERRENCE, BUT
                  DID NOT GET A MACHINE MALFUNCTION INTERRUPT. MEMORY PARITY
                  NOT WORKING CORRECTLY.

               5. CODE HALTS AT LOCATION "38" ANYTIME (MACHINE MALFUNCTION).
                  CONDITION CODE IN PSW INDICATES SPECIFIC CAUSE OF INTERRUPT

                  CONDITION CODE            CAUSE
                  ______________            _____

                  0000                 POWER RESTORE (SHOULD FOLLOW POWER
                                                                FAILURE)
                  X001                 POWER FAILURE
                  0010                 PARITY ERROR ON INSTRUCTION FETCH
                  X100                 PARITY ERROR ON DATA FETCH

                  THE OLD PSW IS SAVED IN LOCATIONS "20 - 27", AND
                  CONTAINS THE STATE OF THE MACHINE WHEN THE MACHINE
                  MALFUNCTION INTERRUPT WAS TAKEN.
       NOTE:      LOCATIONS "348" AND "34A" SHOULD CONTAIN THE MEMORY
                  ADDRESS WHICH CAUSED THE PARITY ERROR.

               6. CODE HALTS AT LOCATION "30" ANYTIME (ILLEGAL INSTRUCTION).
                  THE OLD PSW IS SAVED IN REGISTERS 14 (E) AND 15 (F) OF
                  SET 0 (THE MACHINE IS IN REGISTER SET 0 WHEN THE INTERRUPT
                  IS TAKEN). REGISTER 15 (F) POINTS TO THE LOCATION OF THE
                  ILLEGAL INSTRUCTION.

               7. UNUSUAL CONSOLE DISPLAY FLASHING EVERY SECOND. A NEW
                  OPTION IN THE REMOTE CODE CALLS FOR COUNTING CHARACTERS
                  PER SECOND PASSING THROUGH THE NODE. THE CHARACTER COUNT
                  AND THE HIGH-WATER MARK ARE DISPLAYED ON THE CONSOLE
                  EVERY OTHER SECOND AS FOLLOWS:

                  TYPICALLY, THE LOW-ORDER DIGIT FLASHES 0 TO 1 OR 0 TO 2
                  IF IN THE NETWORK AND TAKEN OVER. IF "CPS" IS ENABLED,
                  THE FLASH OF 1 OR 2 IS UNCHANGED. INSTEAD OF FLASHING THE
                  LOW-ORDER DIGIT OF 0, THE ENTIRE CONSOLE DISPLAYS "CPS"
                  INFORMATION. THE LEFT-HALF OF THE CONSOLE CONTAINS THE
                  HIGHEST SECOND'S COUNT OF CHARACTERS SINCE THE LAST NODE
                  CRASH (HIGH-WATER MARK). THE RIGHT-HALF OF THE CONSOLE
                  DISPLAYS THE CURRENT SECOND'S CPS COUNT, REFLECTING THE
                  CURRENT TRAFFIC ON THE MACHINE.

               8. PASSTHROUGH COUNT ON CONSOLE FOR OVER 256 PASSTHROUGHS.
                  THE 2ND BYTE FROM THE RIGHT ON THE CONSOLE DISPLAYS THE
                  NUMBER OF PASSTHROUGH CIRCUITS ON THIS NODE. SINCE ONLY
                  8 BITS ARE AVAILABLE FOR COUNTING, THERE IS A PROBLEM IF
                  THERE ARE OVER 256 PASSTHROUGHS ON THE MACHINE. THE
                  PROBLEM IS SOLVED BY DISPLAYING 1 TO 3 ON THE LOW-ORDER
                  DIGIT INSTEAD OF 0 TO 2. THEREFORE, IF THERE ARE 260
                  PASSTHROUGH CIRCUITS ON A NODE, THE PASSTHROUGH COUNT
                  FIELD ON THE CONSOLE WILL DISPLAY "04", AND THE LOW-ORDER
                  DIGIT FLICKERS BETWEEN 1 AND 3.


       NOTE:   FOR MORE DETAILED INFORMATION ON RELEASE OF VERSION 422
               ENGINE REMOTE CODE CONSULT THE FOLLOWING DOCUMENTS:

               (RFORKISH:33)RPA422.DOC - DESCRIBES NEW FEATURES ADDED TO
                                         VERSION 422
               (RFORKISH:33)CES422.DOC - PROVIDES TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION
                                         OF NEW CODE ADDED TO VERSION 422.
               (RFORKISH:33)DBS422.DOC - NEW CLASS OF ASSEMBLY OPTIONS FOR
                                         DEBUGGING AND PERFORMANCE MEASURE-
                                         MENT.
               (RFORKISH:33)FE422.DOC  - DESCRIBES REMOTE CODE HALTS AND
                                         DISPLAYS.
               (RFORKISH:33)PVCFUN.DOC - FEATURES AVAILABLE WITHIN PVC
                                         PACKAGE
               (RFORKISH:33)CONF02.DOC - DESCRIBES HOW TO CONFIGURE PVC
                                         ON A REMOTE.


