TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  UPGRADE OF TYMNET ENGINE TO "ENHANCED ENGINE"


               THIS BULLETIN PROVIDES SOME TIPS AND TYPICAL PROBLEMS
               ASSOCIATED WITH UPGRADING A TYMNET ENGINE TO RUN WITH
               "ENHANCED MICROCODE".

       1.      THE ROM & I/O BOARD SHOULD HAVE PROM CHIPS MARKED "E15'-00
               THROUGH E15'-23". THE MAPPING PROMS ON THIS BOARD SHOULD
               BE MARKED "EM15'-0 & EM15'-1".

       2.      THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD SHOULD BE STRAPPED FOR THE FOLLOWING
               OPTIONS:
                               OPTION X - PIN 2 TO PIN 3
                               OPTION Y - PIN 2 TO PIN 3
                               OPTION Z - PIN 2 TO PIN 3

       3.      ON THE CPU BACKPLANE, SLOT 4 CONNECTOR 0, THE FOLLOWING
               TWO JUMPERS SHOULD BE REMOVED:
                               PIN 122 TO PIN 222
                               PIN 134 TO PIN 234

       4.      ASYNCHRONOUS CARD ADDRESSES WILL DEPEND ON THE .TYM FILE
               FOR YOUR CONFIGURATION.
               THE NORMAL ADDRESS RANGES FOR THE ASYNC CARDS ARE:

                               ADDRESS RANGE           ASYNC CARD
                               *************           **********

                               91 - 97                 ASYNC CARD #1
                               99 - 9F                 ASYNC CARD #2
                               A1 - A7                 ASYNC CARD #3
                               A9 - AF                 ASYNC CARD #4

               THE "ENHANCED 256 PORT" ADDRESS RANGE IS AS FOLLOWS:

                               ADDRESS RANGE           ASYNC CARD
                               *************           **********

                               C1 - C7                 ASYNC CARD #1
                               C9 - CF                 ASYNC CARD #2
                               D1 - D7                 ASYNC CARD #3
                               D9 - DF                 ASYNC CARD #4
                               E1 - E7                 ASYNC CARD #5
                               E9 - EF                 ASYNC CARD #6
                               F1 - F7                 ASYNC CARD #7
                               F9 - FF                 ASYNC CARD #8

               IF THE .TYM FILE SPECIFIES:

               NACARD     EQ      4 (OR LESS)
               MICRO      EQ      1
               N.ADA      EQ      0

               THE NORMAL ADDRESS RANGE WOULD BE EXPECTED BY THE CODE.
               ADDRESS THE ASYNC CARDS ACCORDINGLY.

               IF THE .TYM FILE SPECIFIES:

               NACARD     EQ      4 (OR LESS)
               MICRO      EQ      1
               N.ADA      EQ      1

               THE "ENHANCED ADDRESS RANGE" WILL BE FORCED EVEN THOUGH
               THERE ARE 4 OR LESS ASYNC CARDS IN THE CONFIGURATION.

               IF THE .TYM FILE SPECIFIES:

               NACARD     EQ      5 (OR MORE)
               MICRO      EQ      1
               N.ADA      EQ      0

               THE "ENHANCED ADDRESS RANGE" WILL BE FORCED BY THE DEFINITION
               OF 5 OR MORE ASYNC CARDS.


CFB NO.:   17                                        DATE:  JANUARY  9, 1980  

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  TYMNET ENGINE BACKPLANE NOISE PROBLEM


       THIS BULLETIN HIGHLIGHTS A POTENTIAL NOISE PROBLEM WHICH IS
       CURRENTLY UNDER EXAMINATION BY ENGINEERING AND WHICH COULD MANIFEST
       ITSELF IN A NUMBER OF WAYS DEPENDING ON MACHINE CONFIGURATION,
       BACKPLANE REVISION, AND MACHINE LOADING. THE PROBLEM IS NOT
       ABSOLUTELY IDENTIFIABLE AT PRESENT BUT IS KNOWN TO BE CONNECTED
       TO VARIOUS CHARACTERISTICS OF THE MUX (I/O) BUS.

       THE PROBLEM WAS FIRST IDENTIFIED IN THE NETWORK SUPERVISORS
       AND REPRODUCED IN A LAB ENVIRONMENT. IN THE CASE OF SUP MACHINES, IT
       EXHIBITED ITSELF IN THE FOLLOWING MANNER:
       DMA ACCESS ADDRESSES TO CORE WERE BEING CORRUPTED CAUSING DATA FROM
       DISC TO BE STORED IN INCORRECT MEMORY LOCATIONS. ILLEGAL INSTRUCTION
       CRASHES (WHERE THE INSTRUCTION FETCHED WAS IN FACT CORRECT COULD
       ALSO BE ANOTHER MANIFESTATION OF THIS PROBLEM). TECHNICAL SUPPORT
       AND ENGINEERING WORKED ON THIS PROBLEM AND FOUND THAT THE LOCATION
       OF THE SYNC I/F WITHIN THE MACHINE HAD A MARKED EFFECT ON SUSCEPTIBILITY
       TO ERRORS. THUS FAR OUR TESTING HAS INDICATED THAT MOVING THE SYNC
       I/F TO THE SLOT DIRECTLY BENEATH THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD (I.E. SLOT 3
       OF THE UPPER CPU CHASSIS) HAS ELIMINATED THE ERRORS THAT WE WERE
       MONITORING.

       YOU ARE RECOMMENDED TO MAKE THIS CHANGE TO ANY ENGINE THAT IS
       SUFFERING FROM SPORADIC CRASHES ATTRIBUTABLE TO INVALID MEMORY
       REFERRENCES. IN PARTICULAR, I WOULD RECOMMEND THIS BE DONE ON
       LARGE CONFIGURATIONS SUCH AS THE PUBLIC/PRIVATE NETWORK SUPERVISORS
       TOGETHER WITH ANY LARGE ISIS/REMOTE NODES.
       AN ECO TO CORRECT THIS PROBLEM AND REVERT TO NORMAL CONFIGURING
       SHOULD BE FORTHCOMING WITHIN THE NEXT FEW WEEKS.

EFFECTIVE CHANGE:              REMOVE SYNC CARD FROM CURRENT SLOT AND
                               REINSTAL IN SLOT 3 CPU CHASSIS. (REMOVE
                               RACK0/TACK0  JUMPER BETWEEN PINS 122 AND
                               222, CONNECTOR 0 , SLOT 3)
                               INSTAL JUMPER BETWEEN PINS 122 AND 222
                               ON CONNECTOR 0 OF THE SLOT FROM WHICH YOU
                               REMOVED THE SYNC CARD.


CFB NO.:   18                                        DATE:  FEBRUARY  1, 1980 

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  5-VOLT NOISE PROBLEM ON TYMNET ENGINE EXPANSION CHASSIS


PROBLEM:       TYMNET ENGINES WITH DUAL CHASSIS (DMA CAPABILITY) ARE
               CURRENTLY IN THE FIELD. IT HAS BEEN NORMAL PROCEDURE TO
               SEND THESE CONFIGURATIONS INTO THE FIELD WITH THE CONNECTOR 0
               TERMINATOR ON THE LOWEST (SLOT 0) SLOT  IN THE MACHINE AND
               THE CONNECTOR 1 TERMINATOR ON THE SLOT DIRECTLY ABOVE THE
               LOWER CONNECTION POINT FOR THE DMA CABLE. IN THE PARTICULAR
               CASE WHERE NO CARDS ARE INSTALLED IN THE LOWER 16 SLOTS IN
               THE MACHINE, A POTENTIAL PROBLEM HAS BEEN FOUND IN THE
               AMOUNT OF NOISE OBSERVED ON THE 5 VOLT FEEDS TO THE LOWER
               CHASSIS, THE ONLY LOAD PRESENTED BEING THE PULL-UP LOAD OF
               TERMINATORS. THIS COULD CAUSE A POTENTIAL PROBLEM OF NOISE
               BEING INJECTED ONTO THE MEMORY ADDRESS, MEMORY DATA, OR I/O
               BUS VIA THE TERMINATORS. THIS PROBLEM IS MINIMISED AS PC
               CARDS ARE ADDED TO THE LOWER 16 SLOTS, PROVIDING SUFFICIENT
               LOAD TO DAMPEN THE NOISE.

ACTION:        IN THE PARTICULAR CONFIGURATION INDICATED ABOVE, MOVE THE
               CONNECTOR 0 TERMINATOR UP TO SLOT 1, LOWER SECTION OF
               THE CPU CHASSIS. MOVE THE CONNECTOR 1 TERMINATOR (FOR THE
               (MEMORY SENSE/DATA BUSSES AND I/O BUS) TO THE LOWEST SLOT
               OF THE CPU CHASSIS.

RESOLUTION:    TECH SUPPORT IS WORKING WITH ENGINEERING IN PROVIDING AN ECO
               WHICH WILL EFFECTIVELY ELIMINATE NOISE ON THE 5 VOLT LINE IN
               AN UN-LOADED CONFIGURATION.


CFB NO.:   19                                        DATE:  FEBRUARY  4, 1980 

REV LEVEL:  0                                DATE CHANGED:  DECEMBER 20, 1985 

TYPE:  HARDWARE
HARDWARE:  ENGINE
SUBJECT:  POWERING DOWN THE TYMNET ENGINE


WARNING:       BOTH THE LAMBDA AND PIONEER MAGNETICS POWER SUPPLIES HAVE
               EXCEPTIONALLY LONG HOLD-UP TIMES, IN ORDER FOR THE SYSTEM
               TO SUSTAIN MOMENTARY LOSSES OF POWER WITHOUT INTERRUPTION
               TO THE D.C. VOLTAGES ON THE SYSTEM. THE HOLD-UP ENERGY OF
               THE SUPPLY IS STORED IN A LARGE CAPACITOR, INTEGRAL TO THE
               SUPPLY, WHOSE DISCHARGE RATE IS DEPENDENT ON THE AMOUNT OF
               HARDWARE CONFIGURED INTO THE SYSTEM.

               THIS MEANS THAT WHEN YOU DROP POWER TO THE SYSTEM EITHER
               FROM THE CONSOLE KEY SWITCH OR THROUGH THE AC SUPPLY, D.C.
               VOLTAGES ARE STILL BEING DELIVERED TO THE BOARDS UNTIL THE
               STORED ENERGY IS DISSIPATED FROM THE CAPACITOR. THIS IS
               REFLECTED IN THE LED "L3" ON THE MULTIFUNCTION CARD REMAINING
               LIT FOR A PERIOD OF TIME (DEPENDING ON DISCHARGE RATE) AFTER
               POWER SHUT-OFF.
               CARE SHOULD BE TAKEN IN WAITING FOR THAT LED TO EXTINGUISH
               PRIOR TO REMOVING BOARDS FROM THE SYSTEM DURING MAINTENANCE
               ACTIVITIES.


